{
  "texts": [
    "Still, from a machine ethics perspective, (S2) deserves attention as it captures aspects of divine command theory and legal positivism; i.e., given that humans have gathered exhaustive moral knowledge of a certain domain (e.g., determined the actions that support human well-being) and are able to implement it as input-action-commands.",
    "For instance, if one adopts the view that machines are merely tools for human ends, extreme forms of machine-sacrifice or machine-exploitation may be irrelevant.",
    "66 While (S2) might have some appeal for the prospect of moral machines, it makes less sense from a human perspective.",
    "Simply put, people are less likely to cooperate if there are no self-directed incentives (even Kant's Kingdom of Ends assumes some form of obligations to oneself).",
    "The more common strategy, and the most extensively studied strategy in economy and behavioral ecology, is to be rational in the sense of maximizing self-interest:"
  ]
}